st Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":11,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":42,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":67,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Hugh Treverbyn was born in 1248, in Polruan, Cornwall, England, his father, Odo De Treverbyn, was 18 and his mother, Emma de Cardinan, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Theosanna."},"et":{"1248–":"1248–Surnud","1248–Male":"1248–Surnud","1254–1325":"1254–1325","1276–1314":"1276–1314","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1228–Female":"1228–Surnud","1228":"1228","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1314":"1314","1325":"1325","1276":"1276","1254":"1254","1230":"1230","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Treverbyn, Cornwall, England":"Treverbyn, Cornwall, England","Polruan, Cornwall, England":"Polruan, Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1248–":"1248–Kuollut","1248–Male":"1248–Kuollut","1254–1325":"1254–1325","1276–1314":"1276–1314","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1228–Female":"1228–Kuollut","1228":"1228","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1314":"1314","1325":"1325","1276":"1276","1254":"1254","1230":"1230","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Treverbyn, Cornwall, England":"Treverbyn, Cornwall, England","Polruan, Cornwall, England":"Polruan, Cornwall, England"},"fr":{"1248–":"1248–Décédé","1248–Male":"1248–Décédé","1254–1325":"1254–1325","1276–1314":"1276–1314","1230–Male":"1230–Décédé","1228–Female":"1228–Décédée","1228":"1228","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1314":"1314","1325":"1325","1276":"1276","1254":"1254","1230":"1230","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Treverbyn, Cornwall, England":"Treverbyn, Cornouailles, Angleterre","Polruan, Cornwall, England":"Polruan, Cornouailles, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Hugh Treverbyn est né en 1248, à Polruan, Cornouailles, Angleterre, son père, Odo De Treverbyn, avait 18 ans et sa mère, Emma de Cardinan, avait 21 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Theosanna."},"de":{"1248–":"1248–Verstorben","1248–Male":"1248–Verstorben","1254–1325":"1254–1325","1276–1314":"1276–13